<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Commander Jeered at Dniester Commemoration Rally </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Commander Jeered at Dniester Commemoration Rally </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1906121994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1120 
GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1906121994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Valeriy Demidetskiy, </F>
Anatoliy Kholodyuk] 
  [Text] Kishinev [Chisinau], 19 Jun -- The second 
anniversary of the Bendery tragedy was commemorated in the 
Dniester region today. 
  Exactly two years ago, this area on the banks of the 
Dniester 
river was engulfed in a bloodbath, which left hundreds dead and 
thousands refugees. The madness was halted on 21 July 1992 when 
an agreement was signed in Moscow between Moldavia [Moldova] and 
Russia and a contingent of combined Russian, Moldavian, and 
Dniester peacekeeping troops was sent into the conflict zone. 
Thanks to their efforts, a fragile peace has been maintained in 
the area and talks have begun on finding a peaceful settlement 
for the crisis. Russia and the CSCE are mediating at these. 
This was announced at a rally today in Bendery attended by 
thousands in memory of those killed. 
  At the rally, a speech by 14th Army Commander General 
Aleksandr Lebed was greeted by whistles when he criticized the 
leadership of the Dniester region, accusing it of corruption and 
reluctance to solve the conflict by peaceful means. Among other 
things, the general said in his speech that the Tiraspol leaders 
repaid Russia with base ingratitude when it sent its fighters to 
Moscow during last year's October events. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

