<F P=100> Turkmenistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Premier Comments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Premier Comments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1906112294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1101 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1906112294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Glazovskaya] </F>
  [Text] Ashkhabad 19 June TASS -- Turkmen President 
Saparmurad Niyazov leaves for Turkey today for an official 
visit. Summit talks there will take two days, after which he 
will have several days of rest in that country at the invitation 
of Turkish President Suleyman Demirel. 
  A memorandum on cooperation is expected to be signed during 
the visit. It will further develop the already close 
cooperation ties between the two neighbouring countries, which 
believe that they are related to each other by the spirit, 
language, and ethnic origin. 
  This is going to be Niyazov's fourth visit to an Asian 
country over the recent period of time. The first three 
countries he visited were Iran, Malaysia, and Indonesia. 
  A new political-geographic zone is being formed in that 
region following the disintegration of the Soviet Union, Turkmen 
Deputy Prime Minister Boris Shikhmuradov, who shares Niyazov's 
ideas, told ITAR-TASS. It includes the Indian peninsula, part 
of the Near and Middle East, Central Asia, the Caspian and Black 
Sea basins. According to Shikhmuradov, Turkmenistan's situation 
changed in the new geographic zone. It moved from the outskirts 
of Central Asia to the centre of the new political-geographic 
structure, which focused on it the interest of both Western and 
Asian countries. 
  Taking into account the fact that the natural and manpower 
resources of the region, as well as its scientific and 
technological potential, are truly enormous, the Turkmen 
leadership and its president find it expedient to make use of 
them on the basis of the mechanism of bilateral and multilateral 
systems, without inventing or creating new ones. A series of 
Niyazov's recent visits is in line with that task, Shikhmuradov 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

