<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cooperation With NATO To Be Discussed After Fleet Division </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cooperation With NATO To Be Discussed After Fleet Division </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506183094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1537 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506183094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The criteria for cooperation between NATO and the 
Ukrainian Navy would not be discussed before the Black Sea Fleet 
is divided between Ukraine and Russia, General Antonio Milani, 
deputy commander of the NATO southern flank, told journalists in 
Sevastopol where he arrived at the invitation of the Ukrainian 
armed force command. 
  He met with Vice Admiral Volodymyr Bezkorovaynyy, commander 
of the Ukrainian Navy, in the city. 
  Milani said that his visit to Sevastopol had nothing to do 
with the tense situation there and that his party would not meet 
with the Crimean leadership. 
  He emphasized that Ukraine was a sovereign state which had 
to 
tackle its domestic problems on its own. 
  Following his meeting with Milani, Bezkorovaynyy told 
INTERFAX-Ukraine that his country badly needed cooperation with 
NATO in the framework of the Partnership for Peace program 
which, he thought, marked the start of reorienting military and 
political blocks to the maintenance of peace. 
  Bezkorovaynyy said that cooperation between the Ukrainian 
armed forces and NATO and planning of joint activities at the 
initial stage had been discussed in the framework of the program. 
  He added that exchange of experts who would concentrate on 
specific issues in interaction between the Ukrainian Navy and 
NATO had been discussed at the meeting. 

</TEXT>

