<F P=100> Uzbekistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Rejects Eurasian Union Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Rejects Eurasian Union Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706105394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1027 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1706105394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Uzbekistan's Foreign Minister Saydmukhtar 
Saydkasymov said that the Kazakh President Nursultan 
Nazarbayev's proposal of a Eurasian Union is an attempt to 
restore the former USSR. He was speaking in Tashkent on Friday 
[17 June] at a meeting with the heads of the diplomatic corps 
accredited in the Republic. 
  Saydkasymov said the CIS has not exhausted its opportunities 
yet and a Eurasian Union would mean a return to the past. 
"Uzbekistan links its future with the sovereignty obtained by 
the Republic," he said. 
  Kazakhstan's Ambassador to Uzbekistan Nazhameden Iskaliyev 
told INTERFAX that "every state has the right to express its 
opinion on issues in which it has an interest." Iskaliyev 
believes that the idea of an Eurasian Union would be discussed 
at the September summit of the heads of CIS states. 
  "Of course, certain corrections will be introduced into the 
document, nevertheless it should be treated with great 
attention," Iskalilyev said. 

</TEXT>

