<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Immaterial' if Armenia Supplied Arms to Karabakh </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Immaterial' if Armenia Supplied Arms to Karabakh </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706181394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1442 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1706181394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature No. 115 (605) by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy and edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] In an exclusive interview with Interfax, the 
military adviser to President Ter-Petrosyan and chief inspector 
of the Armenian armed forces Gurgen Dalibaltayan said that in 
terms of both quantity and quality the Armenian army met the 
technical requirements of the Transcaucasian region. But, he 
said, the armsrace launched by certain countries of that region 
compelled Armenia to work constantly on the technical potential 
of its army. 
  Under the treaty on conventional weapons, Armenia could have 
no more than 220 tanks, 220 other armored vehicles, including 
135 MICV's, 100 combat planes and 50 combat helicopters. It can 
have no more than 60,000 troops. 
  According to Dalibaltayan, the armed forces were brought up 
almost to their full strength and sufficiently well equipped 
with weapons and hardware. They were still wanting officers 
but, Dalibaltayan said, an all-arms army college was to open in 
Armenia this year. 
  Several think tanks related to the national Defense Ministry 
were working on Armenia's military doctrine. The staff under 
President Ter-Petrosyan would come out with a draft doctrine of 
their own, Dalibaltayan said. 
  Whether or not Armenia supplied Nagorno-Karabakh with 
weapons 
and army hardware, was absolutely immaterial, he said, because 
in the course of combat operations the Karabakh defense forces 
had captured enormous stocks of weapons and hardware, materiel 
and ammunition. 
  A sufficient number of Armenian volunteers went to defend 
the 
sovereignty of Karabakh, Dalibaltayan said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

