<H3> <TI>   Israeli Foreign Minister on Crimea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Israeli Foreign Minister on Crimea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1806143994 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 2000 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1806143994 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] Interviewed by a UNIAN 
correspondent, Shimon Peres, head of the Israeli external 
political department, noted that in spite of this being his 
"first time in Odessa," he "understood why this beautiful city 
is the soul of all the world's Jews." 
  Asked whether he could draw a parallel between the issue of 
Crimean autonomy in Ukraine and that of Palestine in Israel, the 
minister answered in the affirmative: "Undoubtedly so. In both 
cases, efforts to improve relations are more expedient than 
amending borders. Under conditions of tension, there is no 
point in talking about borders. An atmosphere of mutual respect 
should be created. This would guarantee success in our 
negotiations in the United States. Progress begins when the 
sides realize that force gives in to intelligence." 

</TEXT>

