<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Latest on Implementation of Social Accord Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Latest on Implementation of Social Accord Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Agrarians May Sign Accord Agreement </H4>

<F P=102> LD1906143294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1231 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1906143294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On Sunday Russian Vice-Premier Aleksandr Zaveryukha 
told Interfax that the Agrarian party, its faction in the State 
Duma and the Central Committee of the Union of Workers of the 
Agro-Industrial Complex could yet be expected to sign the civic 
accord agreement after they met, to clear up positions, with 
President Yeltsin on June 27. 
  The Vice-Premier in charge of agriculture was elected a 
member of the State Duma on the ticket of the Agrarian party 
which brings together almost 200,000 men and women. Russia's 
one and only Agrarian labor union boasts a membership of almost 
16 million. 
  According to Zaveryukha, the Agrarians had failed to sign 
the 
civic accord agreement owing to differences of opinion on 
government support for the agro-industrial complex. In 
addition, he said, the labor union and the government differed 
on the issue of social insurance. 
  But, Zaveryukha said, the Agrarian faction in the State Duma 
supported the president- and government-backed draft of the 
Federal budget although those who had signed the civic accord 
agreement opposed the draft. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

