<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clash Between Skokov, Shmakov Bodes Ill for Trade Unionists </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clash Between Skokov, Shmakov Bodes Ill for Trade Unionists </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK1806133694 Moscow KOMMERSANT-DAILY in Russian 18 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> MK1806133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMMERSANT-DAILY </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Yekaterina Achalova report: "FITUR Board Plenum. Trade </F>
Unions Change Ally"] 
  [Text] Addressing yesterday's sitting of the executive 
committee of the Federation of Independent Trade Unions of 
Russia [FITUR], Federation head Mikhail Shmakov accused Yuriy 
Skokov of attempting to break up the FITUR and create on its 
basis another trade union organization. The sharpness of the 
accusation was provoked by the fact that Skokov is building 
contacts with regional trade unions bypassing the FITUR's 
central leadership and actually stripping them of control. 
  Earlier, the FITUR cooperated with the Russian Union of 
Industrialists and Entrepreneurs [RUIE] whose president Arkadiy 
Volskiy masterminded the creation of a Trilateral Conciliation 
Commission -- the RUIE, the FITUR, and the government -- so that 
trade unions could refer their demands directly to the 
government. In the wake of October 1993 the government stopped 
delegating its ranking representatives to the commission's 
sessions, which rendered the RUIE's cooperation with the FITUR 
less interesting. When Volskiy's centrists suffered complete 
defeat in the December elections and finally departed the list 
of influential political forces, all reasons for FITUR-RUIE 
cooperation were totally lost. Trade unions bosses and 
entrepreneurs started to look around for new partners. 
  An apolitical mode of life under the leadership of Mikhail 
Shmakov looked to union bosses not exciting enough, and they 
started to look for a new Big Brother for political gambles. 
Producers of commodities suited the role best. Four major 
trade unions associations of the Urals, Siberia, the Northern 
Caucasus, and the Central Volga, decided to secure support from 
Skokov and signed an interaction agreement with him. 
  This agreement may soon lead to a split of the Federation. 
Offended by the behavior of Skokov, who ignored all proposals 
for a meeting and who played up to his subordinates behind their 
boss's back, Mikhail Shmakov intends to press for the annulment 
of the agreement. But since the FITUR is a typical example of a 
political partner always on the lookout for someone to form a 
bloc with, it is doubtful that union officials will listen to 
their chairman and give up so opportune an idea as an alliance 
with Skokov. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40745 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov118_b_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-118 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Filatov: Crime Approaching Emergency Proportions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Filatov: Crime Approaching Emergency Proportions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1806151994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1310 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1806151994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sergey Filatov, leader of the presidential 
administration, declared that the criminal related situation in 
Russia "is on the brink of an emergency one" and this explains 
the necessity of Boris Yeltsin's decree on urgent measures to 
protect the population from banditism and organized crime. 
  "When as many as ten explosions are registered over 24 
hours, 
it means that bandit formations force their ideology of life to 
the society," he said in his interview with Interfax Saturday. 
  At the same time Filatov pointed out that part of the 
society 
expresses its disagreement with Yeltsin's decree due to the 
provision on possible detention of the suspected for 30 days. 
He recognized that this method "has been actually taken from 
the decree on the state of emergency." 
  In Filatov's opinion, those, who say that this provision of 
the presidential decree should be compensated in the legal sense 
"by removing the old fear of the people in the face of the 
unrestricted power of the law enforcement bodies," are quite 
right. Filatov believes that it is possible to achieve this 
involving the conciliatory commission in charge for the 
implementation of the Agreement on Public Accord. 
  Filatov is known to be chairman of this commission. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

