<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Stepashin on Establishing New Anticrime Directorate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Stepashin on Establishing New Anticrime Directorate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706223994 Moscow Mayak Radio Network in Russian 2100 GMT 
17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1706223994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Mayak Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A special directorate for searching and detaining 
criminals will be set up in Russia in the very near future, 
Sergey Stepashin, director of the federal counterintelligence 
service, has said at a news conference in Vladivostok. He also 
said the special services of Japan, North Korea, and China had 
recently stepped up their activities in the Maritime Kray. 
  Replying to a question by an ITAR-TASS correspondent on how, 
in the light of the latest decree by the Russian president on 
the immediate measures to protect the population against 
banditism and other forms of organized crime, local 
counterintelligence and interior directorates would interact, 
Stepashin said the federal counterintelligence service next week 
would sign an agreement with Viktor Yerin, interior minister of 
the Russian Federation, which would define the interaction and 
division of powers between the two departments. In Sergey 
Stepashin's words, it has been decided to put an end to 
competition between the departments. From now on 
counterintelligence officers, jointly with the interior 
ministry, will deal in real earnest with cases of corruption in 
the top echelons of state power and a number of organized crime 
groups using the channel of international terrorism and drugs 
smuggling. The federal counterintelligence service will help 
the interior ministry with equipment. 
  Sergey Stepashin said the president in the very near future 
would sign a decree setting up a special directorate in the 
federal intelligence service and territorial directorates, 
accordingly. Thus, counterintelligence will get the opportunity 
to participate directly in searching, detaining, and eliminating 
those who encroach upon the law and people's rights and lives. 
  The director of the federal counterintelligence service also 
visited the major port town of Nakhodka. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

