<H3> <TI>   Hopes Duma Approves 1994 Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hopes Duma Approves 1994 Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1906141494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1231 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1906141494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian Prime-Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin hopes 
that on June 22 the State Duma will endorse the final draft of 
the Federal budget for 1994. 
  Talking to newsmen at Moscow's Vnukovo-2 airport before 
boarding a flight for Milan, Chernomyrdin said the Federation 
Council, too, would be able to see what was what in the economy 
and would endorse the budget. 
  According to Chernomyrdin, the Duma committees had done a 
great job. After the draft budget was presented to the Duma on 
May 11, he said, they came out with more than 300 amendments to 
that document. Doing it all over again would make no sense, 
Chernomyrdin said. His impression was, some individuals were 
simply afraid to have nothing to do. 
  In Chernomyrdin's view, it was about time for the government 
to work on a draft budget for 1995, instead of going back to 
what it had already done. 
  Chernomyrdin said the government had pledged to come out 
with 
a draft budget for 1995 in September. 

</TEXT>

