<H3> <TI>   `Optimism' of Deputy Economy Minister Cited </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Optimism' of Deputy Economy Minister Cited </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2006112394 Moscow TRUD in Russian 17 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM2006112394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow TRUD </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report from the "This is the News" roundup: </F>
"Optimism Against Gloomy Background"] 
  [Text] "On the whole, the necessary conditions for 
advancing along the path of reforms have been created in 
society," Russian Federation First Deputy Minister for the 
Economy Yakov Urinson declared yesterday at a government 
sitting, summing up the preliminary results of the first six 
months of 1994. 
  By his assertion, the government program adopted earlier to 
stabilize the situation in the economy is beginning to show 
"tangible, positive results, and talk about the collapse and 
fatal line of the economy are unsubstantiated." 
  As for specific figures, however, according to data from the 
Ministry for the Economy the GDP (in fixed prices) fell by 
almost 18 percent compared to the same period last year. 
Overall, the volume of industrial output went down by 27 
percent, falling by almost half in the machine building and 
metalworking sectors. 
  According to expert evaluations, money supply will increase 
by roughly 60 percent (8 percent per month). Inflation, by 
comparison with December of last year, will comprise around 90 
percent. Industrial producers' wholesale prices will double. 

</TEXT>

