<H3> <TI>   Israeli Foreign Minister Offered Missile Launchers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Israeli Foreign Minister Offered Missile Launchers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1606090994 Jerusalem THE JERUSALEM POST in English 16 Jun 
94 p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> TA1606090994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem THE JERUSALEM POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by David Makovsky] </F>
  [Excerpts] Ukraine has offered to sell Israel missile- 
launchers for Israeli satellites, participants in a meeting 
between Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk and Foreign Minister 
Shim'on Peres said in Kiev yesterday. 
  Peres said Israel would consider the offer. 
  Amid a dispute over the Jewish Agency's aliya activities in 
Ukraine, Peres and Ukrainian leaders agreed yesterday to set up 
cultural centers in each other's countries. [passage omitted] 
  Peres told reporters yesterday that while anti-Semitic 
incidents have occurred in Ukraine, he was convinced that 
Ukrainian leaders were genuinely trying to combat this 
phenomenon. 
  In his talks in Kiev yesterday, Peres' Ukrainian counterpart 
also suggested that the two countries establish consulates in 
Haifa and Odessa. Ukrainian leaders also extended invitations 
both to President 'Ezer Weizman and Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin 
to visit Kiev. 
  Bilateral agreements were signed in the areas of investment, 
taxation, police, science, and culture. [passage omitted] 
  [A report by Hemi Shalev on page 12 of Tel Aviv MA'ARIV in 
Hebrew on 16 June adds: "Ukraine offered to try to use its good 
relations with Damascus to create yet another channel of 
communications between Israel and Syria. 
  ["Ukrainian President Kravchuk told Peres that his country 
considers Israel `a strategic neighbor,' and that he hoped the 
agreements Peres will sign today would provide `a firm legal 
basis' to the relations between the two countries." 
  [The report notes that Peres complained to his Ukrainian 
counterpart about Ukraine's votes in the United Nations and 
other international organizations, and that the Ukrainian 
foreign minister replied: "I never dreamed that I would be 
hosting in Kiev an Israeli foreign minister who would voice his 
complaints and would also manage to convince me. You must 
understand that getting used to our independence and getting 
over the past takes time."] 

</TEXT>

