<H3> <TI>   Russia, Moldova Differ on 14th Army Withdrawal Schedule </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia, Moldova Differ on 14th Army Withdrawal Schedule </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906093194 Moscow RIA in English 0820 GMT 9 Jun 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0906093194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow RIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, June 9, RIA -- Russia and Moldova still have 
some differences on the time-table for the withdrawal of the 
Russian 14th Army from that republic. The issue was discussed 
at a press conference on the 9th round of the Russian-Moldovan 
talks in Moscow Wednesday. 
  Ambassador at large Vladimir Kitayev, chief Russian 
negotiator, said that in the estimates of military experts the 
process would take about 4 years, or slightly less. Nicolae 
Osmokescu, first deputy foreign minister of Moldova, who heads 
the Moldovan delegation at the talks indicated that in 
accordance with the official position of his country, the 14th 
Army should be withdrawn no later than December 31, 1995-January 
1, 1996. The heads of the two delegations confirmed that 
certain understanding had been reached on the issue, and the 
discussion of the timetable would be continued at the next 
round. This is the only disagreement which divides the parties 
working on the legal status, procedure and timeframe for the 
withdrawal of the Russian troops temporarily stationed in 
Moldova. The two sides said that certain progress recently 
achieved in the Transdniester settlement. Similarly, progress 
has been recorded in the efforts at finalising other documents 
complementing the main agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

