<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parties in Former Republics Support Eurasian Union </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parties in Former Republics Support Eurasian Union </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1906165894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1517 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1906165894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The forum Towards a New Accord which was attended in 
Moscow by representatives of 17 parties and 30 movements from 
all former USSR's republics except Turkmenistan called on the 
leaders of all the new independent states to refute territorial 
claims on one another and publicly say so. 
  Igor Smirnov, chairman of the International Movement for 
Democratic Reforms ruling body, Arkadiy Volskiy, President of 
the Russian Union of Industrialists and Entrepreneurs, Gennadiy 
Zyuganov, leader of the Communist Party of the Russian 
Federation, Nikolay Ryzhkov, former Soviet prime minister, and 
State Duma and Federation Council members were among the 
participants of the forum. 
  The forum supported the idea of a Eurasian Union that had 
been put forward by Kazakh President Nursultan Nazarbayev and 
called on the CIS heads of state to consider it from the 
viewpoint of what is good for their peoples. They supported the 
proposal made by Ryzhkov that a CIS parliament had to be set up. 

</TEXT>

