<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Petroleum Club To Promote Joint Projects </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Petroleum Club To Promote Joint Projects </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106101094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0957 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2106101094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Vanichkin] </F>
  [Text] Washington June 21 TASS -- The establishment of a 
Russian-American petroleum club -- a new nongovernmental and 
nonprofit organisation -- was announced by Yuriy Shafranik, 
Russian minister of fuel and power, here on Monday. 
  This organisation will promote an accelerated development of 
Russia's petroleum sector and establish cooperation between 
Russian and American companies, Shafranik told ITAR-TASS. 
  One of the main tasks of the club will be to establish 
direct 
contacts between large petroleum companies of the two countries, 
which will render unnecessary go-betweens which quite often only 
discredit joint projects, he said. 
  "Yet another project which, I hope, will be discussed within 
the framework of the club envisages transition from the sale of 
American oil-well equipment to Russia to its manufacture in our 
country. 
  "With the availability of relatively small financial 
resources, the Russian side can turn out a very large array of 
such equipment at defence-industry enterprises subject to 
conversion to civilian production. Large American petroleum 
companies support this idea," the minister said. 
  Final details of the work and organisational structure of 
the 
club are to be discussed in the coming days within the framework 
of the Russian-U.S. intergovernmental commission for economic 
and technological cooperation, Shafranik emphasised. 
  The club is expected to include directors of petroleum and 
investment companies of the two countries. Its headquarters is 
to be in Moscow and its missions will be located both in Russia 
and the U.S. 
  Shafranik also mentioned as very important events at the 
forthcoming session of the bilateral commission the final stage 
of discussion and a probable signing of an agreement under a 
Sakhalin-2 project which will for the first time give access to 
Russian oil- bearing shelves to an international consortium. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

