Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Conditionally Agrees to Carter Plan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Conditionally Agrees to Carter Plan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006140494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1306 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006140494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang will agree to former U.S. President Jimmy 
Carter's plan concerning its nuclear program if a comprehensive 
solution is found to all other problems, North Korean Ambassador 
to Moscow Son Sung-pil told the State Duma's international 
affairs committee on Monday. 
  He said that after consultations in Pyongyang and a 
telephone 
conversation with Washington officials, Carter had unveiled a 
plan for a U.S. rejection of sanctions against North Korea and 
the resumption of bilateral talks broken off in March. 
Simultaneously, Son said, Washington has agreed to provide to 
North Korea a technology for a nuclear reactor working on light 
water. 
  If the plan works, North Korea will fully comply with the 
nuclear non-proliferation treaty though IAEA's inspection of its 
nuclear installations will be impossible while the negotiations 
are under way, he said. 
  At the same time, the ambassador warned that his country 
would take proportionate, but strong measures in response to any 
international sanctions which would be seen as "a declaration of 
war and would respond accordingly." 
  On the Russian Foreign Ministry's initiative for an 
international conference on the issue, Son said his country had 
"a certain interest" in it. However, "we cannot accept it" if 
the forum is intended to try to bring pressure on North Korea, 
the ambassador said. 
  Son spoke of holding a series of talks with the Russian 
Foreign Ministry to try to get the details of the conference 
proposal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

