<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Committee, DPRK Envoy on Korean Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Committee, DPRK Envoy on Korean Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006200194 Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy in Russian 
1800 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2006200194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Committee for International Affairs discussed 
the situation on the Korean peninsula at the Russian State Duma 
today. Son Sung-pil, the North Korean ambassador to Russia, 
spoke to deputies. 
  [Correspondent Ivan Trefilov] North Korea will meet war with 
war, and the specific measures will depend on the particular 
sanctions that the world community takes against the republic, 
the North Korean diplomat said. At the same time, the DPRK is 
willing to come to talks at any time and to settle the nuclear 
problem peacefully. In this connection, North Korea has 
manifested some interest in the proposal by the Russian Ministry 
of Foreign Affairs for an international conference to be held on 
the nuclear problem of the Korean peninsula. However, if the 
conference is intended to bring pressure to bear, the DPRK will 
not be able to agree to this, the North Korean ambassador 
stressed. 
  In the diplomat's view, there has been some progress in 
settling the nuclear problem since the visit to the DPRK by 
former U.S. President Carter. The American visitor handed over 
an official U.S. proposal: the abandonment of sanctions; the 
supply to North Korea of light water reactors; and a third round 
of U.S.-DPRK talks. In return for this, the DPRK must retain 
international monitoring at its nuclear facilities. 
  In the view of the North Korean diplomat, this proposal 
could 
form the basis for a comprehensive settlement of the nuclear 
problem on the Korean peninsula. 
  Ivan Trefilov, for Ekho Moskvy at the State Duma. 

</TEXT>

