<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin To Sign Treaty With European Union </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin To Sign Treaty With European Union </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006141994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1355 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On Monday the Russian Deputy Minister for Foreign 
Economic Relations Georgiy Gabunia told INTERFAX that Russia and 
the European Union have reached agreement on a draft treaty for 
partnership and cooperation and on Tuesday the document is 
expected to be formally approved by the EU Council. 
  President Boris Yeltsin and the leaders of EU countries plan 
to sign the document in Corfu, Greece on Friday. 
  According to Gabunia, the package of documents related to 
the 
treaty, including a joint declaration and letters of exchange, 
consists of some 100 typewritten pages. Under the treaty the 
European Union will recognize Russia as a country with a 
transitional economy, not one with a state-run system of trade. 
  Gabunia said that talks on the agreement have been going on 
for two years. The section on trade in commodities has caused 
the greatest difficulties. The sides decided to offer each 
other most- favored-nation status in trade. The treaty has 
sections regulating business and investment activities, in 
particular the formation and operation of companies, the flow of 
capital and payments. It describes cooperation in finance, 
economy, culture and crime- prevention. 
  The implementation of the agreement will be controlled by a 
Cooperation Council formed of high-ranking government officials: 
ministers or deputy prime-ministers. Under the draft the 
council is to assemble onece a year. Routine control will be 
carried out by a Cooperation Committee consisting of officials 
of a lower rank and experts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

