<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gaydar Seeks Interparty Cooperation in Japan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gaydar Seeks Interparty Cooperation in Japan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106082494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0747 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2106082494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vyacheslav Bantin] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo June 21 TASS -- Russia's Democratic Choice 
(RDC) party believes that the territorial problem in relations 
with Japan "is a long-term task which has no easy solutions", 
RDC chairman Yegor Gaydar told ITAR-TASS. He arrived in Tokyo 
on Monday for a private visit to discuss ways of cooperation 
between the RDC and Japan's largest opposition 
Liberal-Democratic Party (LDP) and attend an international 
seminar on investment problems. He was due to meet with members 
of the LDP and Japanese Foreign Ministry leadership on Tuesday. 
  "While recognising the existence of a territorial problem, 
we 
consider that any approaches to its solution should be based on 
the results of the Russo-Japanese summit talks in Tokyo in 
autumn last year," Gaydar pointed out. He expressed an opinion 
that the problem could be resolved only when public consensus 
develops in Russia and Japan on how that could be done. 
  Touching upon the RDC's foreign contacts, Gaydar said the 
party intends to conclude cooperation agreements with a number 
of foreign parties, similar to that which was concluded with the 
Japanese Liberal-Democratic Party last week. 
  "Strengthening political ties with those political forces 
abroad, which are interested in a normal development of Russia, 
is an important element of our calm work to overcome xenophobia 
in Russia and to counter ideas, which are being spread in the 
country by some of our political opponents, about some 
conspiracy against Russia and her isolation in the world," 
Gaydar said. 
  "We attach much importance to developing contacts with Japan 
and regard the LPD as one of our serious and long-term 
partners," the RDC chairman pointed out. 
  "The conclusion of an agreement with the LDP is not linked 
with hopes to get financial support from it," he said. "We may 
not permit ourselves to make use of financial support from 
foreign political parties and intend to build our relations with 
them on the basis of equal partnership," Gaydar said. 
  The RDC chairman said "Russia will succeed in maintaining 
political stability within at least the next six months despite 
the existence of forces which are interested in destabilising 
the situation in the country". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40830 </DOCNO>
