<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Votes For Smaller `94 Military Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Votes For Smaller `94 Military Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2006143494 Moscow Russian Television and Dubl Networks in 
Russian 2309 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2006143494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television and Dubl Networks </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report; from the "Aty-Baty" program] </F>
  [Text] We continue our review of the leading military and 
political events, of which the main item is the adoption of the 
state budget for 1994. The budget allocation for national 
defense was one of the fundamental complications in the 
ratification of this annual financial plan. May we remind you 
that at the first reading of the draft budget, the State Duma, 
by a majority of votes, adopted the government proposal and 
ratified the military budget in the amount of 37 trillion rubles 
[R]. The Duma's decision was turned down by the Federation 
Council, which deemed that the expenditure for military needs 
should be R56 trillion, and the draft was returned to the lower 
house for further examination. The State Duma, in considering 
this issue again, came to the conclusion that it could allocate 
no more than an additional R4 trillion for all military 
expenditures. Thus, the maximum figure the military can count 
on in 1994 is R41 trillion. 
  It is important to note that the shortfall in the amount 
requested by the Defense Ministry will most probably be the 
substantial reason for not satisfying social needs of servicemen 
in the current year, primarily in respect to their housing 
needs, daily life, and medical services. The most unexpected 
thing in this whole affair was that Boris Nikolayevich Yeltsin, 
president of Russia, the person on whose backing the Ministry of 
Defense counted most of all, supported the Duma's initiative in 
limiting the 1994 military budget. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

