BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Taranov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 20 Jun (ITAR-TASS) -- Vladimir Lukin, 
chairman of the Russian State Duma Committee for International 
Affairs, thinks that Russia should "more closely coordinate" its 
actions with Washington on the issue of a possible introduction 
of sanctions against the DPRK. 
  This issue was discussed today at a closed session of the 
Duma Committee for International Affairs. The DPRK's ambassador 
extraordinary and plenipotentiary to Russia participated in the 
meeting. 
  Vladimir Lukin told the ITAR-TASS correspondent that the 
discussion showed that "the North Korean position is still not 
quite clear." According to him, the DPRK "is either trying to 
`bargain' for better conditions, or gain the time necessary to 
conclude work on the creation of a nuclear weapon." 

