<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discuss Investment Projects </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Discuss Investment Projects </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006163494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1439 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006163494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy; edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] President Akayev pins great hopes on broader 
economic cooperation with Japan and on greater Japanese 
investment in specific projects. 
  Akayev told Japanese Ambassador Kiji Watanabe during the 
ceremony of the presentation of credentials, that since the 
first days of independence, Bishkek and Tokyo had been 
maintaining relations of trust and friendship. "No other 
country helps us more than Japan in promoting economic 
restructuring and the reorganization of the banking and 
communication systems," he said. 
  On the same day, Kyrgyz Prime Minister Apas Zhumagulov met 
with Japanese businessmen to discuss the role of Japan in the 
economic restructuring program. He proposed that Japan invest 
in the Kyrgyz defense, machine-building and agriculture-related 
industries. 
  Zhumagulov said that only about 8 percent of Kyrgyzstan's 
hydro-energy resources were used, and that Japan's participation 
in the construction of small, medium and big hydro-power plants 
might benefit both countries. 
  As an example of bilateral cooperation he referred to the 
plant for the production of semiconductors which is being built 
in the south of Kyrgyzstan. This plant is expected to 
manufacture 1000 tonnes of poly-and mono-crystal silicon a year. 
  Zhumagulov told Interfax that relations between Kyrgyzstan 
and Japan were broadening and that he expected much of the 
Kyrgyz-Japanese committee for economic cooperation, which is to 
meet in Tokyo next November. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

