<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Offensive on Afghan Border `Thwarted' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Offensive on Afghan Border `Thwarted' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006124894 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1100 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2006124894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] We continue to receive reports of death and injury 
in Tajikistan, as well as attempts by armed guerrillas to force 
their way into the Republic from Afghanistan. Our correspondent 
will tell you in more detail about the situation there: 
  [Reporter Mikhail Nikulin in Tajikistan -- identified by 
caption] It was right here, on the so-called Pyanj sector, that 
a massive offensive by armed detachments of the Tajik opposition 
was supposed to take place on the eve of the inter-Tajik talks 
in Tehran. According to reports from military intelligence, 
such a decision was taken at a meeting of field commanders of 
several formations based in northern Afghanistan. Russian 
border guards, together with the command of the collective 
peacekeeping forces, have taken additional measures to 
strengthen this section of the border. 
  [V. Novikov, chief of staff of Russian border guards in 
Tajikistan -- identified by caption] We can now say that those 
strategic schemes, which the enemy and the opposition were 
hatching, have effectively been thwarted. We can see that the 
situation here is stabilizing. But, on literally every 
centimeter of the border, you can still sense that it is 
explosive, ready to explode at any moment. 
  [Nikulin] But this temporary lull prevails only on this 
section of the 1,200 km border. Elsewhere [pauses] 
  [Novikov, interrupting] Shelling is continuing, attacks are 
continuing, provocations of various kinds are continuing. 
  [Nikulin] During the first 20 days of June alone there have 
already been over 10 armed provocations on the border, as a 
result of which the opposition lost over 15 militants. 

</TEXT>

