<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Troops Observe Withdrawal Schedule </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Troops Observe Withdrawal Schedule </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006134194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1321 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006134194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Kuchina] </F>
  [Text] Riga June 20 TASS -- Russian troops are being pulled 
out of Latvia according to schedule, the press centre of the 
North-Western Army Group reported on Monday. There will be not 
a single unit or military installation here after August 31, 
apart from the radar station in Skrunda. 
  Air and naval forces, border troops and air defence units 
have already left this Baltic state. Out of 177 units, over 50 
percent were redeployed, three-quarters of combat materiel and 
95 percent of ammunition were carried away. 
  Less than ten percent of material resources are to be 
loaded. 
There were 361 military and 34 housing compounds in Latvia. 
Russian troops have now less than a third of military and about 
50 percent of housing compounds. The rest were handed over to 
local authorities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

