<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Calls for Stronger Economic Ties With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Calls for Stronger Economic Ties With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006134694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1322 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006134694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demidenko and </F>
Mikhail Melnik] 
  [Text] Donetsk 20 June TASS -- "Unless the price of 
Ukrainian goods is lower than that of Russian goods, customs 
checkpoints must continue to function," Ukrainian President 
Leonid Kravchuk said. 
  Speaking at a meeting with the workers of the Azovmash 
machine-building plant in Mariupol, Ukrainian port city on the 
Azov Sea, on Monday, Kravchuk said that "we cannot allow the 
scanty Ukrainian market to become empty. If we open up the 
borders now, the major part of consumer goods and agricultural 
produce will be taken out to the Russian Federation." 
  "Presently, due to objective reasons we have a situation 
when 
the same goods made in Russia and Ukraine have different 
production costs," Kravchuk continued. He believes that 
production cost largely depends on the price of energy carriers, 
the bulk of which Ukraine receives from Russia. 
  "If Ukrainian enterprises paid for oil and gas as much as 
Russian plants and fabrics pay, then we would need no customs 
checkpoints. Trade between Ukraine and Russia would become state 
business, not private," he said. 
  Kravchuk stressed that "trade relations between Ukraine and 
Russia must develop and expand." "Such great powers must have 
strong friendly and economic ties," he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

