<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Hopes for NATO Accord Signing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Hopes for NATO Accord Signing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006150394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1339 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006150394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature] </F>
  [Text] Moscow hopes that soon after the Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev signs the Partnership For Peace program in 
Brussels on Wednesday yet another program "Russia-NATO" will be 
signed. 
  As a senior foreign ministry official has recalled in an 
interview with INTERFAX, the "Russia-NATO" program was submitted 
to NATO's Headquarters just a month ago. "This substantive 
document mirrors our vision of relations with NATO, Russia's 
role and place in Europe and elsewhere. It would certainly be 
lovely to sign two programs at once, but the men at NATO will 
apparently need time to study the Russian proposals. So, we do 
not dramatize the situation, nor do we intend to spur events 
deliberately," the diplomat said. 
  He did not rule out that in Brussels Kozyrev and NATO 
leaders 
might sign a declaration of intent to promote cooperation and 
partnership. "We feel the Russia-NATO program could be the 
platform for that," he said. 

</TEXT>

