<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Votes for Peacekeepers in Abkhazia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Federation Council Votes for Peacekeepers in Abkhazia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106103294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1010 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2106103294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow June 21 ITAR-TASS -- The Russian Federation 
Council today met behind closed doors to debate the sending of 
Russian troops to Abkhazia to police the zone of conflict 
between Georgia and its break-away autonomy. The upper house 
eventually approved the move. 
  Defence Minister Pavel Grachev told journalists that the 
absolute majority in the upper chamber voted for conducting the 
peace-keeping operation in the region". 
  "To me, this is an order to act," Grachev said. "As soon as 
the mine-clearing operation is reported over, we will get down 
to the peace-keeping operation proper, including posting 
sentries and setting up checkpoints," he said. 
  The defence minister said that the operation will begin with 
the relocation of two battalions from Batumi and paratroopers 
from Gudauta. Later, two more battalions will be airlifted from 
the Leningrad and Privolzhskiy (Volga) Military Districts to 
reinforce the group. A total of 3000 men will take part in the 
peace-keeping mission in Abkhazia. 
  Grachev said preparatory work was done over the past few 
days, particularly as concerns the mine-clearing operation which 
defused a great amount of explosives and bombs in the area. 
Control points were set up, communication lines laid and 
material and other resources were stocked. 
  Asked about the funding of the peace-keeping operation in 
Abkhazia, the defence minister expressed the hope that the 
deputies would soon adopt a decision on funding the mission from 
sources other than the ministry's budget. He said the mission 
would require the outlay of 10 to 11 billion roubles until the 
end of this year. 
  It is not yet clear whether other Commonwealth member states 
will take part in the mission, Grachev said. But the question 
about it will be raised at the Commonwealth summit in September, 
the minister said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

