<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dniester Releases Ilascu Group Detainee Godiac </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dniester Releases Ilascu Group Detainee Godiac </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2106100894 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 2010 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2106100894 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chisinau BASAPRESS, 16/6/1994 -- Petru Godiac, 
condemned by a Dniester court to two years of imprisonment 
following the Ilascu group's trial, was set free on 12 June, 
declared to BASAPRESS on behalf of Ivan Fuchiji, minister of 
interior of Tiraspol [Dniester Republic], Oleg Palamarchuk, 
chief of the Dniester Ministry of Interior's Secretariat. 
Palamarchuk refused to give any information on the conditions 
of detention of the remaining detainees. Valentin Dolganiuc, 
leader of the parliamentary block of the Alliance of 
Christian-Democratic Popular Front of Moldova [AFPCDM], 
confirmed in an interview to BASAPRESS that Godiac was set free 
and presently is with his parents in Stefan-Voda. Petru Godiac, 
born on 1 September 1967, in the village of Talmaz, Suvorov 
district, completed a secondary education, is married, and most 
recently worked as a driver at the Tiraspol spinning mill for 
the department of transportation. He was arrested on 12 June 
1992 and condemned at the Ilascu group's trial, according with 
Article 227, the second point of the Criminal Code of the 
Moldovan Soviet Socialist Republic. 

</TEXT>

