<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier Receives Japanese Businessmen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Premier Receives Japanese Businessmen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006145194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1359 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kyrgyz Prime Minister Abbas Dzhumagulov called on 
Japanese businessmen to play a part in reforming his country's 
economy. When he met with them in Bishkek Monday [20 June], he 
called on Japanese businessmen to invest in the reconstruction 
of defense, engineering and food processing industries. 
  Dzhumagulov believed that as little as 7 to 8 pct of the 
country's rushing water is used to generate electricity and that 
Japanese participation in construction of small, medium, and 
large hydro power stations would be profitable to both countries. 
  He also invited them to invest in the construction of a 
factory manufacturing semi-conductors in the south of Kyrgyzstan. 
  Dzhumagulov emphasized that he pinned great hopes on the 
Kyrgyz-Japanese Economic Cooperation Commission, which he heads. 
He will attend its session in Tokyo next November. 
  Dzhumagulov said that the government had set up a 
reconstruction and development bank which reflects the Japanese 
way of doing things. The bank will mobilize state resources to 
finance and credit priority projects and support small and 
medium business in priority fields. 

</TEXT>

