<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier Submits Ministers' Resignations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Premier Submits Ministers' Resignations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2106102994 Tallinn BNS in English 1456 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2106102994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, June 20, BNS -- Prime Minister Mart Laar 
on Sunday formally sent to President Lennart Meri his formal 
proposals to relieve Finance Minister Heiki Kranich and Culture 
and Education Minister Paul-Eerik Rummo from their duties, 
Government Spokesman Ain Saarna said. 
  According to the country's laws, the president now has got 
three days to make his decision. 
  Kranich and Rummo, both from the Liberal Democratic Party, 
entered their resignations last Tuesday. The Liberal Democratic 
Party on the same day announced its stepping out from the Pro 
Patria-led ruling coalition. 
  Recent media reports have mentioned Kalle Jurgenson, deputy 
chairman of the Pro Patria faction in the parliament, as a most 
likely candidate for the post of the finance minister, as well 
as Tonis Lukas, the director of the Estonian National Museum, as 
a possible new culture and education minister. Both have denied 
having received proposals to accept the positions. 
  Also mentioned have been Andres Lipstok, local 
administration 
leader in the western Laanemaa county, as possible new finance 
minister, and Tiit Sinissaar, head of the Pro Patria faction in 
the parliament, as minister of culture and education. 
  Estonia currently also has the position of the defense 
minister vacant. Official reports name Raul Opik as still the 
main candidate for the office. 
  The prime minister in interviews earlier has expressed hope 
that the new ministers will be sworn in at summer emergency 
sessions of the parliament, due at the end of this month. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

