<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Speaker Attacks Proposed Referendum </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parliament Speaker Attacks Proposed Referendum </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006141694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1346 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006141694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladas Burbulis] </F>
  [Text] Vilnius June 20 TASS -- Speaker of the Lithuanian 
parliament Ceslovas Jursenas called attempts by the right-wing 
party "Union of Fatherland" (Lithuanian Conservatives) to 
organise a referendum on economic issues as "efforts to 
undermine the state's foundations". 
  The party led by Vytautas Landsbergis and Giadiminos 
Vagnorius demands that the main item of the poll should be a 
100-time indexation of people's deposits at savings banks, the 
speaker said at a news conference on Monday which was broadcast 
by national radio. 
  He did not accept last Friday signatures of 413,110 
Lithuanians in support of a referendum, which were collected by 
a sponsoring group of conservatives. 
  Explaining reasons for his move, Jursenas said that "the old 
law is still in force. It lays down that such signatures should 
be handed over to the presidium of the Lithuanian parliament, an 
institution which is not provided for in the new constitution". 
  Besides, sheets with signatures, hence the will of people, 
were not formalised with the final act, as it is provided for by 
the previous law. Therefore, he had no powers from parliament 
to receive 43 volumes of signatures. 
  On the other hand, amendments to the law on referendum, 
which 
were adopted by parliament recently, were not approved by the 
Lithuanian president, which was well known to the sponsoring 
group. The legislature is to solve this "legal problem" on 
Tuesday. 
  Leader of Lithuanian Conservatives Vytautas Landsbergis who 
also held a news conference on Monday, described the speaker's 
actions as "a demonstration of disrespect for the will of nearly 
500,000 Lithuanian voters and a desire to win time". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

