<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zyuganov: Russia on Verge of `Criminal Dictatorship' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zyuganov: Russia on Verge of `Criminal Dictatorship' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1806165894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1523 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1806165894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Leader of the Russian communist party Gennady 
Zyuganov believes that the country is on the threshold of 
criminal dictatorship. On Saturday he addressed the sitting of 
the forum Towards New Accord in Moscow. Representatives of 17 
parties and 30 public organizations and movements from former 
Soviet republics except Turkmenistan participated in the sitting. 
  According to Zyuganov, "dictatorship is inevitable" in the 
case that "neither replacement of the course, nor refusal from 
political revenge, nor formation of a government of national 
confidence take place in the near term and priority trends in 
the development of the agrarian industrial complex, military 
industrial complex, education, science, and culture are not 
determined." 
  The sitting discussed problems and prospects of economic and 
political unification of the former Soviet republics. As said 
President of the Russian Union of Industrialists and 
Entrepreneurs Arkadiy Volskiy, it would be necessary to Moscow 
to invest 10,000 trillion rubles in order "to transfer to 
self-subsistence economy" that is to manage without economic 
cooperation with the former Soviet republics. 
  The volume of the inter-republican trade was 21 percent of 
the USSR GNP, reported former USSR premier Nikolay Ryzhkov. At 
the same time he said that out of 15 Soviet republics only 
Russia and Turkmenistan had favorable trade balance. "Beginning 
with 1917 Russia always gave more than it received," Ryzhkov 
declared. 
  He warned about the danger "of ignoring and silencing" of 
the 
issue on the borders within the former Soviet Union and reported 
there were 70 points on its territory "which can trigger the 
issue on the borders." 
  In Ryzhkov's opinion, "the CIS appeared to be lacking vital 
capacity and has not justified its tasks." A future voluntary 
union, he said, should be open not only for former Soviet 
republics but for other countries of Europe and Asia which will 
express their wish to join it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

