<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Taken on Reunification With Former Republics </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Taken on Reunification With Former Republics </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106105294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1028 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2106105294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow June 21 ITAR-TASS -- More than one-third of 
Russians polled in a recent survey by the Public Opinion Fund 
said it is in the interests of the country to reunify Russia 
with other former Soviet republics in one state. But one-fourth 
of the respondents in the poll said they were against any 
reunification with any country. 
  Asked what countries should be given preference in the 
unification process, three percent favored Azerbaijan, four 
percent Armenia, 24 percent Belarus, four percent Georgia, 13 
percent Kazakhstan, three percent Kirgizia [Kyrgyzstan], four 
percent Latvia, three percent Lithuania, eight percent Moldavia, 
four percent Tajikistan, three percent Turkmenia, four percent 
Uzbekistan, 24 per cent Ukraine and three percent Estonia. 
  Thirty-four percent called for reunification with all former 
Soviet republics. 
  Only 13 percent of those polled were uncertain. 
  The poll of 1200 respondents was conducted in June, and its 
results were published in the BUSINESS WORLD WEEKLY on Tuesday. 

</TEXT>

