<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Drafts Bill on Prosecutor General's Office </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Drafts Bill on Prosecutor General's Office </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106112994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1006 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2106112994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Federation Council and Duma are to receive from 
President Yeltsin Tuesday or Wednesday a bill on the Prosecutor 
General's Office. The Council's Chairman Vladimir Shumeyko 
announced in the parliament's upper house on Tuesday that 
Yeltsin will submit the document as part of his legislative 
initiative. 
  Shumeyko explained that Yeltsin is offering lawmakers the 
opportunity to first discuss the role of the Prosecutor 
General's Office and only "then choose a person to run it." 
  So far Aleksey Ilyushenko has been acting as Prosecutor 
General, despite the fact that he has proved unpopular in the 
Federation Council. 
  After Shumeyko's statement, the issue of making the proposal 
on a Prosecutor General part of the session's agenda was put to 
a vote at several legislators insistence. However, it was not 
included in the agenda because the motion did not collect the 
necessary number of votes. 

</TEXT>

