<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Sends Greetings to Religious Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Sends Greetings to Religious Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106091894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0905 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2106091894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 21 TASS -- President Boris Yeltsin has 
sent a message of greetings to participants in an 
interconfessional conference, which opened here on Tuesday, on 
the subject "The Christian Faith and Human Animosity". 
  Greeting the spiritual leaders of most of Christian churches 
and religious associations that traditionally exist in CIS and 
Baltic countries, the president pointed out that their 
"aspiration to find ways for the Christians' full-scale 
participation in overcoming human animosity in the post-Soviet 
space" is close and understandable to him. 
  "Over long years of militant atheism, the souls of many 
people have become depleted and have grown hard, harbouring 
indifference and hatred. All that is a nutrient medium for 
social and inter-ethnic conflicts, extremism in politics, 
tension in society". 
  Yeltsin expressed the conviction that "the involvement of 
Christian communities of various confessions in the constructive 
peace-making processes will be of great benefit. Religious 
leaders can stay the hand of a killer by force of wise words and 
by virtue of their moral prestige, help people to start dialogue 
and convince them of necessity to return to peace and mutual 
understanding". 
  "I believe that you will pool your efforts and will actively 
promote the advancement of the peoples of the newly independent 
states towards accord and cooperation in the spirit of freedom, 
mutual tolerance and well-wishing. 
  "I will continue to support the joint peace-making efforts 
of 
CIS and Baltic Christians and your cooperation with the 
believers of other religions and non-religious people in common 
concern for the well-being of our states," the message said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

