<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nationwide Poaching-Control Operation Begins </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nationwide Poaching-Control Operation Begins </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006071994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0709 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006071994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 20 TASS -- A nation-wide 
poaching-control operation called "Zaslon" which was launched on 
Monday, will protect Russia's national wealth, said here on 
Monday Rear-Admiral Sergey Skalinov, deputy commander of Russian 
naval border forces, in an interview with ITAR-TASS. 
  According to the admiral, all ships took their assigned 
positions and started fulfilling their duties. 
  The poaching-control operation is being conducted on the 
Barents, Baltic, Black, Azov and Caspian seas, Lake Chudskoye, 
the Amur and Ussuri rivers. It involves, along with border 
forces, ships of the Russian Navy, Aviation, the Customs Service 
and other state structures. 
  In the opinion of Skalinov, experience accumulated during 
the 
first stage of a previous poaching-control operation which was 
carried out in the Pacific, enabled military authorities to 
deploy forces in a short period of time and establish 
cooperation between them. 
  The admiral said that the second stage of the 
poaching-control operation in the Pacific was launched 
successfully on Monday. Vice-Admiral Nikolay Kudinov, commander 
of naval forces of Russian border troops, is in charge of this 
operation. 
  "The main task of these large-scale operations is to prevent 
the pillage of Russia's national wealth, along with strict 
observance of international norms and rules," the admiral 
concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

