<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trial of 1991 Coup Plotter Varennikov Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trial of 1991 Coup Plotter Varennikov Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006145094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1306 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006145094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Russian Supreme Court's Military Collegium is to 
continue the trial of one of the 1991 coup leaders Valentin 
Varennikov, a spokesman for the Military Collegium confirmed in 
an interview with Interfax on Monday. Varennikov faces charges 
of high treason and conspiring with the aim of seizing power. 
  Varennikov is the only leader of the 1991 coup, who did not 
agree to being granted political amnesty, announced by the State 
Duma on February 23, 1994, and who demanded that the trial be 
continued. The cases against the other defendants were 
terminated. 
  Varennikov denied all charges brought against him during the 
preliminary investigation and in court. His interests will be 
represented by lawyer Dmitriy Shteynberg. 
  Shteynberg's request for terminating the case in the absence 
of any criminal content in Varennikov's actions, was turned 
down, because only the court may take such a decision. 
  Among the witnesses who are expected to appear in court are 
former commander in chief of the Soviet airborne troops 
Vladislav Achalov, Russia's Deputy Defense Minister Boris 
Gromov, former Soviet president Mikhail Gorbachev and former 
Soviet defense minister Dmitriy Yazov. 
  The hearings will be chaired by Major-General Viktor Yaskin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

