<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Farmers Need R9 Trillion To Harvest Crops </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Farmers Need R9 Trillion To Harvest Crops </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1906143794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1231 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1906143794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] If the Russian farming sector does not have nearly 
nine trillion rubles credits, much of the next harvest would be 
lost, Aleksandr Nazarchuk, State Duma Agricultural Committee 
chairman, told Interfax Sunday. 
  The credits, he said, must be granted on easy terms rather 
than at the unbearable discount rate of 210 percent. He 
complained that the agricultural sector was neglected as far as 
financing was concerned. 
  The updated draft budget that was supported by the Agrarian 
Party in the Duma would appropriate over 10.8 trillion rubles, 
of which over four trillion as support of most important 
industries, for agricultural needs. As of mid-June, however, as 
little as 9.26 and 1.94 pct of these amounts, respectively, have 
been made available, Nazarchuk said. 
  He added that the Finance Ministry had promised to make as 
much money available to the farming sector as the budget had 
appropriated. 
  Even if it does, however, the Agrarian Party cannot rule out 
the possibility of protest actions undertaken by the Russian 
peasants. The national convention of peasants may have a 
significant role to play in such actions. The date of the 
convention will be set by the Agricultural Workers Collective 
Action Council which will meet on June 24. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

