<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Navy Opposes State Control Over Naval Nuclear Sites </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Navy Opposes State Control Over Naval Nuclear Sites </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006163794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1511 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006163794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia's Navy regards as unacceptable the powers of 
the Federal Atomic Surveillance Committee to control naval 
nuclear power installations. 
  The Committee's Spokesman Yuriy Rogozhin told Interfax, his 
office received a letter from the Navy Commander, Admiral Felix 
Gromov, proposing interdepartmental inspection over nuclear 
safety in the navy. 
  He said the committee is currently empowered to license army 
units for running their nuclear or radioactive facilities and 
inspect them. These powers were backed up by a decree issued by 
the president on November 12, 1992. 
  The committee believes interdepartmental inspection instead 
of state control could lead to incidents at naval nuclear sites. 

</TEXT>

