<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Concern Over Safety of Nuclear Stations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Concern Over Safety of Nuclear Stations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2006163894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1511 GMT 20 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2006163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sergey Adamchik, a senior official at the Russian 
State Nuclear Safety Agency, told Interfax that Russia at 
present cannot modernize the power units of first generation 
nuclear stations that do not meet modern safety standards. He 
said that because of inadequate financing the agency cannot 
afford rapid checking of the reactors. "The government can 
economize on everything, except safety at nuclear facilities," 
Adamchik said. 
  He said safety at first generation power units was discussed 
at an international conference in Obninsk held under the 
auspices of the International Nuclear Energy Agency. In 
addition to Russia it was attended by 12 West and East European 
countries as well as Japan. The conference stressed the burning 
need to modernize first generation stations depending on the 
economic and political situation in each country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

