<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on `Russia-NATO' Protocol </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on `Russia-NATO' Protocol </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2106152594 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 22 Jun 94 
First Edition p 6 </F>

<F P=103> PM2106152594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Andrey Kozyrev: We Proceed on the </F>
Basis of Pure Pragmatism in Cooperation with NATO"] 
  [Text] Russia's Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev announced 
Monday [20 June] that during his visit to Brussels, and in 
addition to the document on joining NATO's "Partnership for 
Peace" initiative, he will also sign a protocol concerning 
Russia's direct cooperation with NATO. 
  Emphasizing the second document's importance in a 
conversation with journalists, the Russian Federation's foreign 
minister said that Russia is interested "not only, and maybe 
even not so much, in signing the 'Partnership for Peace' 
program, but in the Russia-NATO program." 
  An ITAR-TASS correspondent was told by the minister's 
adviser 
Galina Sidorova that the protocol on cooperation with the North 
Atlantic alliance is a "ramified document." She reminded him 
that the program for Russia's cooperation with NATO, which was 
elaborated by Russian experts, was presented by Defense Minister 
Pavel Grachev to his NATO partners during his recent visit to 
the alliance headquarters. Afterwards, Russian diplomats and 
their NATO colleagues used it as a basis to prepare a document 
acceptable to both sides. Work is still being done on details, 
but Russia's most important wishes have been taken into account. 
"The protocol will incorporate virtually all provisions in the 
program suggested by us to NATO," G. Sidorova said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

