<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Welcomes Approval for Abkhazia Mission </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev Welcomes Approval for Abkhazia Mission </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106122794 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1100 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2106122794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Federation Council's debate on the dispatch of 
Russian peacekeeping forces to the zone of the Georgian-Abkhaz 
conflict is one of the most important events of the day. The 
decision was adopted by a majority of votes. 
  [Correspondent Marina Vasilyeva] Today's session of the 
Federation Council began with a debate on the possibility of 
using the Russian Armed Forces for the peacekeeping operation in 
the zone of the Georgian-Abkhaz conflict. The debate, held 
behind closed doors, lasted over an hour. The president's edict 
was ratified as a result. Journalists learned of this first 
from Pavel Grachev, who represented the Russian president at the 
session. 
  [Begin Grachev recording] The Federation Council has adopted 
a positive decision. The debate was conducted in a proper 
manner. The motion won an absolute majority. Seven deputies 
abstained and another seven were against. All the rest voted 
for the peacekeeping operation in Abkhazia. This is a sign -- 
or, for me, an order -- to get started. In literally two or 
three days' time, once Colonel General Kuznetsov has reported to 
me that all engineering and mine clearance work has been 
completed, we will start on the peacekeeping operation proper -- 
in other words, the deployment of outposts, checkpoints, 
observation points, command points. We will start work. [end 
recording] 
  [Vasilyeva] The decision that was adopted gives the go-ahead 
for a contingent of the Russian Armed Forces, numbering up to 
3,000 volunteers, to be used in the peacekeeping operation, with 
an initial mandate of six months. Committees of the Federation 
Council have been instructed to supervise the implementation of 
this decision. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

