<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev, Christopher To Discuss Korean Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev, Christopher To Discuss Korean Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106155494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1418 
GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2106155494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Dmitriy Chubarov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 21 Jun -- The idea of holding an 
international conference on questions of the security and 
nuclear-free status of the Korean Peninsula looks at the present 
moment more topical than ever. This was stated today by Russian 
Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev before his departure by air for 
Brussels. In the Belgian capital he intends to meet and have 
talks with U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher. 
  "This meeting," the head of Russian diplomacy noted, "is 
being held on the instructions of the two presidents to examine 
the Korean problem and to agree a common approach in the UN 
Security Council." 
  As yet, he added, we do not have sufficiently complete 
information as to what specifically former U.S. President Jimmy 
Carter managed to achieve as a result of his trip to the DPRK. 
A. Kozyrev voiced the hope that his meeting with the secretary 
of state will help shed light on this question. 
  At the same time, he stated, Moscow cannot be satisfied just 
with the assessments of the U.S. side, but intends to be guided 
primarily by its own understanding of the situation, since the 
problem which has arisen has a direct bearing on the sphere of 
Russia's national interests, indeed geographically the Korean 
Peninsula is located much nearer to Russia than to the United 
States. 
  In the course of his visit to the Belgian capital the head 
of 
the Russian Federation's foreign policy department also plans to 
sign the framework document of NATO's "Partnership for Peace" 
program and the "Russia-NATO" protocol to the eponymous 
bilateral cooperation program. 
  This protocol determines, the minister continued, that 
Russia 
and NATO will cooperate in the military-political and 
military-technical sphere on the main elements of the program 
which has already been submitted to Brussels by Russian Defense 
Minister Pavel Grachev. 
  Concerning the situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina, A. Kozyrev 
stated that this question will also be discussed at the meeting 
with W. Christopher. He announced that in Geneva in the near 
future there might be a second ministerial meeting which would 
be primarily devoted to liaison with the warring sides. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

