<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Intelligence Service `Closely Monitoring' Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Intelligence Service `Closely Monitoring' Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106120994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1055 
GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2106120994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Vladimir Solntsev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 21 Jun -- The Foreign Intelligence Service 
of the Russian Federation is closely monitoring the situation 
regarding the nuclear problem on the Korean peninsula and this 
monitoring is being done, among other things, in collaboration 
with representatives of Western special services, experts of the 
Foreign Intelligence Service told the ITAR-TASS correspondent 
today. 
  Replying to a question about the possible emergence of a new 
armed conflict on the Korean peninsula just over four decades 
since the end of the Korean war, the Russian special service 
experts said: For the time being, according to our estimates, 
neither side wants a conflict. The specialists said that so far 
they cannot see that either side has a clear and firm policy 
toward casting the world into global conflict. 
  The experts of the Foreign Intelligence Service 
categorically 
denied speculation that the former Soviet Union virtually 
assisted North Korea [DPRK] to create a nuclear bomb, stressing 
that cooperation between the USSR and DPRK in the nuclear field 
had been carried out for exclusively peaceful ends and under 
international control. In particular some work to train 
specialists was carried out. Apart from this, the USSR supplied 
fuel assemblies for a civilian research reactor under the 
control of the International Atomic Energy Agency. 
  Commenting on the nuclear problem on the Korean peninsula, 
informed Russian circles note that in addition to the problem on 
the surface, each side has its own political objectives and this 
is reflected in the political campaign now under way in the 
world. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

