<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry on Duration of Iraqi Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry on Duration of Iraqi Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106165694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1538 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2106165694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: correspondents Igor </F>
Porshnev, Vitaliy Trubetskoy and others] 
  [Text] Russia's Foreign Ministry believes that if Iraq 
formally declared respect for Kuwait's sovereignty and 
recognized the demarcated frontier, the chances of lifting the 
international sanctions against Baghdad would look brighter, a 
senior Russian diplomat told an Interfax interviewer on Tuesday. 
  He stressed that these sanctions could not last forever and 
would have to be dropped sooner or later best of all by 
civilized means. 
  In his words, "even now there is an explicit erosion of the 
sanctions." "For instance, there is evidence of the Turks 
siphoning oil from the oil pipe-line, going from Iraq. In other 
words, an appropriate process is underway, and the world 
community should take it under control," he said. 
  He argues that the UN Security Council should set a 
six-month 
term for monitoring Iraq's compliance with the Security 
Council's resolution. "Even now one can say that Baghdad has 
fulfilled the UN Security Council's resolution 687 on 
disarmament in full. After this term, the UN Security Council 
could discuss the possibility of lifting or softening the 
sanctions. The Security Council imposed them, and it was for it 
to abolish them," the diplomat stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40988 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov120_a_94021" </HT>


