<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Communications Agreement Signed With PRC </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Communications Agreement Signed With PRC </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106172894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1542 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2106172894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia and China ended talks in Moscow on Tuesday by 
signing an agreement for cooperation in the area of 
communications. 
  The two sides are committed to help improve their 
communications networks and postal services, ensure the transit 
of all types of communications and postal dispatches through 
each other's territory and provide better legal regulation. 
  Russia and China are planning to increase the number of 
telecommunication links from 30 to 90 by the end of this year 
and largely reduce the need for third countries in this sphere, 
Russian Communications Minister Vladimir Bulgak told reporters 
in Moscow. The number of links, telephone and other, will 
eventually be increased to 250 to meet the two countries' needs, 
he said. 
  The two countries reaffirmed the intention to let Beijing 
hook up to Russia's transiberian fiber optic communications due 
to go into operation in 1996. For its part, China is to install 
communications from Harbin to Khabarovsk and Nakhodka and from 
Heihe to Blagoveshensk. 

</TEXT>

