<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Says Retired Troops Pose No Threat to Baltics </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Says Retired Troops Pose No Threat to Baltics </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106132594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1308 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2106132594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 21 TASS -- Most Russian retired military 
living in the Baltic states are elderly people and pose no 
threat to the security of the countries, according to Russian 
Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev who also said that the fact is 
clearly understood by the Baltic leaderships who, however, 
"remain hostages of the political situation". 
  80 per cent of the pensioners are over 60. "They have 
nowhere 
to leave and pose no threat to the national security. Besides, 
they receive pensions from the Russian Defence Ministry", 
Kozyrev told Russian mass media chiefs on Tuesday. 
  "Leaders of the Baltic republics are intelligent people and 
clearly realise that the problem is artificial. However, they 
remain hostages of the political situation", Kozyrev said and 
added that he is pessimistic about an early solution of the 
problem of Russian retired military living in Estonia. 
  The main Russian task is that "military pensioners in the 
Baltics are not offended and humiliated", the minister stressed. 

</TEXT>

