<H3> <TI>   UNESCO Chief on Contacts With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNESCO Chief on Contacts With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106125094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1206 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2106125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By an ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 21 TASS -- UNESCO Director-General 
Federico Mayor began his visit to Moscow with talks with Russian 
minister of science and technology and head of the Russian 
commission of UNESCO Affairs Boris Saltykov. During his first 
working day, the UNESCO chief is also scheduled to meet 
patriarch of Moscow and All Russia Aleksiy II, mayor of Moscow 
Yuriy Luzhkov and Russian mass media officials. 
  Federico Mayor is a leading Spanish scientist and 
biochemist. 
He has written over 50 scientific works, member of several 
academies, and a noted political worker. Mayor has been at the 
helm of the prestigious specialized organization in the U.N. 
system for the past more than six years. UNESCO helps 
strengthen peace, security and cooperation among the people in 
the field of education, science and culture. 
  Before beginning his current visit to Russia, in an 
interview 
with ITAR-TASS, Federico Mayor emphasised that he would like to 
see closer interaction between the two sides in the 
reconstruction and modernization of the Hermitage museum in St. 
Petersburg, and the Russian state library and the Bolshoy 
theatre complex in Moscow. 
  Favouring everyday contacts with Russia, Mayor intends to 
take part in the opening ceremony of a UNESCO bureau in the 
Russian capital. According to him, the international 
organization can make use of Russia's experience in its own 
activities. 
  The UNESCO director-general is expected to be received by 
Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Wednesday. 

</TEXT>

