<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chechen Leader's Aide Questions Russia's Legitimacy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chechen Leader's Aide Questions Russia's Legitimacy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106165094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1319 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2106165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Groznyy may demand the restoration of the USSR if 
Moscow keeps saying the Chechen republic is part of Russia, a 
member of President Dzhokhar Dudayev's staff told Interfax. 
According to the same source the former Soviet leaders would be 
invited to Groznyy for consultations on the issue. 
  A senior presidential spokesman said the Chechen leaders 
recognized the legitimacy and legal acts of only the Soviet 
Union. "As for the legitimacy of the Belovezh agreements that 
caused the USSR to fall apart, the Chechen leaders have big 
doubts about them", the source told Interfax. "The Chechen 
people have the full right to this, because when for the first 
time in their history they took part in the referendum on 
preserving the USSR, they voted "yes"." 
  "If Russia, which does not have a legal reason for 
statements 
that Chechnya is a member of the Russian Federation, keeps 
saying so, Groznyy will reserve the right to call in question 
the legitimacy of the Russian Federation and its leaders", the 
senior source at the Chechen presidential staff said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41011 </DOCNO>
