<H3> <TI>   Naval Commander Views Sevastopol, Black Sea Fleet Proposals </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Naval Commander Views Sevastopol, Black Sea Fleet Proposals </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106172794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1542 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2106172794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sevastopol must become Ukraine's naval stronghold, 
while the Russian Navy can be deployed there as a navy of a 
foreign power, Ukrainian Navy Commander Vladimir Beskorovainy 
said. 
  Speaking in Sevastopol on Tuesday, he said Russia could be 
allowed to deploy its navy there for a period of 15 to 25 years 
after an appropriate leasing agreement was signed. 
  The commander hopes that the problem of sharing the Black 
Sea 
Fleet (BSF) will have been sorted out by the end of next year as 
envisaged by the Yalta agreement. 
  On Speaker of Parliament Alexander Moroz's call for joint 
BSF 
command to be maintained, Beskorovainy described the task as 
technically feasible. However, he stressed that the question 
was purely political amounting to the creation of a military 
alliance in fact. 
  Russia and Ukraine ended the final round of talks in Kiev on 
9 June by compiling a list of warships to be shared with each 
other. However, the question of deployment and sharing the 
existing infrastructures remains unresolved. 
  Beskorovainy also said that a Ukrainian patrol ship would be 
sent to France to take part in a final parade at Rouan early 
next month dedicated to fifty years since the allied nations' 
operation in Normandy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

