<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Foreign Minister Views Cooperation With EU </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Foreign Minister Views Cooperation With EU </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106173294 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
1500 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2106173294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Oleksandr Makarenko, deputy minister of foreign 
affairs, spoke at a briefing at Ukraine's Foreign Ministry today 
on the results of President Leonid Kravchuk's visit to 
Luxembourg and the signing of an agreement on partnership and 
cooperation between Ukraine and the European Union [EU]. The 
deputy minister described the agreement as the beginning of 
Ukraine's integration in the united Europe. He said, in 
particular, that for Ukraine the most important part of the 
document is the political part, which confirms the EU's interest 
in Ukraine's sovereignty, independence, and territorial 
integrity. Regarding purely economic issues, Oleksandr 
Makarenko said, the agreement envisages the withdrawal of any 
restrictions on trade between Ukraine and EU member states. He 
said, however, that although Europe, by this agreement, has 
opened its doors, the speed of our integration will depend on 
the speed of our reforms. 

</TEXT>

