<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-120 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Welcomes Agreements </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Welcomes Agreements </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206083894 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
0500 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2206083894 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] It has been a year since Ukraine and Russian signed 
an agreement on free trade, but in reality there is no free 
trade. This was stated at a briefing at the Ukrainian Ministry 
of Foreign Affairs by Deputy Foreign Minister Oleksandr 
Makarenko. He explained that the reason for this was that 
Russia had 48 exemptions from a list of goods that Ukraine 
imported. These were goods that were of vital importance to 
Ukraine such as energy sources and timber. In the view of the 
deputy minister, the creation of the CIS economic community and 
Ukraine's associate membership of this union should remove these 
discriminatory restrictions. 
  Oleksandr Makarenko acquainted journalists with the results 
of President Leonid Kravchuk's visit to Luxembourg and the 
signing of an agreement on partnership and cooperation between 
Ukraine and the European Union. The deputy minister assessed 
the signing of this agreement as the beginning of Ukraine's 
entry into a united Europe. He in particular stressed that the 
political part of this document which acknowledges the European 
Union's interest in seeing Ukraine as a sovereign, independent 
and territorially integrated state, was of great importance to 
Ukraine. 
  Regarding essential economic issues, Oleksandr Makarenko 
said 
the agreement envisaged the removal of any restrictions on trade 
between Ukraine and European Union member states. At the same 
time he noted that although Europe had opened the door with this 
agreement, the speed with which Ukraine would join it depended 
on the speed of reforms in Ukraine. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

